The National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) yesterday said inflation rate decreased from the 15.63 per cent last December to 15.60 per cent in January 2022. The Statistician General of the Federation, Dr. Simon Harry, broke the news to reporters in Abuja. He said: “In summary and in attempt to make comparison between the January 2022 and December 2021 figures, it is important to note that Headline Inflation for the month of January, 2022 was 15.60per cent, while that of December, 2021 was 15.63 per cent.” He added that Core Inflation for January, 2022 was 13.87per cent, while that of December, 2021 was also 13.87per cent.   Investors jostle for dollar assets as returns hit 20%     ‘Construction, real estate, others major contributors to…     Buhari appoints Bello-Koko NPA MD   - Advertisement - According to him, “Food Inflation for January, 2022 was 17.13 percent compared to 17.37per cent, percent in December 2021.” - Advertisement - The NBS chief noted that urban inflation rate stood at 16.17 per cent year-on-year in January2022 the same with last December figure of 16.17per cent. On the other hand, according to him, Rural Inflation was 15.06 per cent and 15.11per cent in January 2022 and December 2021. On State by State comparison, Harry said, all items inflation on year-on- year basis was highest in Abuja with 18.59 per cent followed by Kogi with 18.28 per cent and Bauchi 17.61per cent. On the other hand, he said, Kwara recorded the lowest with 12.94 per cent followed by Niger with 14.10 per cent and Oyo, 14.19 per cent. “Still on State – by – State, food inflation on a year-on-year basis was highest in Kogi with 22.61per cent followed by Enugu with 19.84per cent and Akwa Ibom (19.67per cent), while Sokoto had 14.18per cent, Bauchi (14.63per cent) and Kaduna (15.01per cent) as the lowest in January 2022,” he said. SPONSORED